Convexity meets curvature
We’ve seen that both \alpha-convexity for a function f and \kappa&gt;\alpha for a Markov kernel imply contraction properties for dynamical systems associated to these objects. These two properties come together in a very nice way when considering Langevin diffusion. Langevin diffusion is a stochastic process on \mathbb{R}^d, governed by the following stochastic differential equation: dX_t=-
abla V(X_t)dt+dB_t where V:\mathbb{R}^dightarrow\mathbb{R} is a potential function and B_t is a standard Brownian motion. One can think of X_t as the trajectory of a particle undergoing random motion in a force field 
abla V. As tightarrow \infty, the law of X_t converges to a unique stationary distribution, given by the Gibbs measure \mu_*=  rac{1}{Z}e^{-V}, with the normalizing constant Z=\int_{\mathbb{R}^d} e^{-
abla V(x)}dx. The rate at which the process converges to its stationary distribution is a well-studied topic, as it suggests natural sampling schemes for distributions that can be written in the form  rac{1}{Z}e^{-V}. In particular, if one assumes that V is \alpha-strongly convex, one is guaranteed exponential convergence of the Langevin diffusion to \mu_*.
